Package: spmixqr
Type: Package
Title: Spatial Quantile Regression with Autocorrelation and Mixtures
Version: 0.4.0
Authors@R: person(c("Kailas", "Venkitasubramanian"), email = "kailasv@gmail.com",
    role = c("aut", "cre"))
Description: Quantile regression for spatial data that accounts for spatial
    dependence and autocorrelation. A conditional-autoregressive (CAR/ICAR) spatial
    random effect, built from a weights matrix derived from queen/rook contiguity,
    distance bands, k-nearest neighbours, or a user-supplied matrix (Leroux et al.
    (2000) <doi:10.1007/978-1-4612-1284-3_4>), absorbs residual spatial
    autocorrelation, with permutation Moran's I diagnostics; the single-region case
    is a maintained spatial-error quantile regression in the lineage of Reich,
    Fuentes and Dunson (2011) <doi:10.1198/jasa.2010.ap09237>. Per-observation
    survey/sampling, frequency, or precision weights are supported with type-aware
    inference. The estimator extends
    to finite mixtures of quantile regressions with spatially varying mixing and
    spatially varying covariate-effect surfaces, reusing the 'mixqr' core (Wu and Yao
    (2016) <doi:10.1016/j.csda.2015.08.013>). A penalised expectation-maximisation
    algorithm carries the CAR precision as a sparse penalty and uses 'mgcv'
    thin-plate, Gaussian-process, or Markov-random-field smooths for the spatial gate
    and slope surfaces. Inference is classification-aware: a fast sandwich and a
    spatial-block bootstrap (recommended for reporting). For point-referenced data a
    scalable nearest-neighbour Gaussian-process Matern precision (Datta, Banerjee,
    Finley and Gelfand (2016) <doi:10.1080/01621459.2015.1044091>) is available as a
    weights-matrix-free alternative to the contiguity CAR. A 'Spatial+' safeguard
    (Dupont, Wood and Augustin (2022) <doi:10.1111/biom.13656>) residualises covariates
    against a spatial smooth to guard against spatial-confounding bias.
